# Language Interpretation

depends on:

```text id="m2f7qe"
literal understanding
and
inferential thinking
```

Figurative language and tone are NOT:

```text id="r6f3qe"
word-for-word
interpretation
only
```

Students learn:

```text id="x9f1qe"
read language
→ notice clues
→ interpret meaning
→ identify emotion
→ explain effect
```

This develops:

* interpretation
* emotional literacy
* vocabulary flexibility
* literary analysis
* expressive understanding

This becomes:

# Author Meaning Thinking

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p5f8qe"
figurative language
=
literal truth
```

or:

```text id="u1f4qe"
tone
=
topic
```

Some may think:

```text id="c7f9qe"
tone
depends
only
on
one word
```

without understanding:

```text id="k3f6qe"
tone
comes from
overall language
```

Students may also:

```text id="n8f2qe"
miss
author emotion
```

Example:

sentence says:

```text id="t4f7qe"
The classroom
was a zoo.
```

students may answer:

```text id="q9f3qe"
animals
were inside
```

instead of recognizing:

```text id="v6f1qe"
room
was noisy
or chaotic
```

because:

```text id="a2f5qe"
figurative language
communicates
ideas
indirectly
```

Tone example:

```text id="g8f4rx"
The author
praised
the effort
warmly.
```

Tone may be:

```text id="v3f9rt"
encouraging
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="j7f2qe"
nonliteral interpretation
and
emotional meaning
```

For Grade 5:

focus includes:

Figurative Language:

* simile
* metaphor
* idiom
* personification
* imagery

Tone:

* emotion
* attitude
* word choice
* mood clues
* author voice

Important idea:

```text id="n4f8qe"
authors
choose language
for effect
```

